    "***\n",
    "### Q2: Assuming you account for what is different about using accuracy versus a loss function, there is still something wrong with using accuracy. What is it? That is, why wouldn't you use accuracy to train a neural network model? \n",
    "(Hint: How does the accuracy surface differ from the MSE or BCE surfaces? What happens right around b=0, w=0?)\n",
    "\n",
    "The accuracy surface is flat and discontinuous, just like a staircase because accuracy rounds continuous predictions to hard 0/1 values before scoring them. This means small changes to w and b produce no change in accuracy at all until a threshold is crossed, where the surface jumps abruptly. Gradient descent needs a smooth, differentiable surface to compute meaningful gradients which is a signal telling the optimizer which direction to move. On the accuracy surface, the vast majority of the space is flat, meaning gradients are zero almost everywhere and the optimizer has no direction to follow. MSE and BCE avoid this by working directly with raw probabilities, producing smooth surfaces that gradient descent can reliably navigate."
   ]
